# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: propeller-aeronautics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] The propeller *advance ratio or coefficient* is a dimensionless number used in aeronautics and marine hydrodynamics to describe the relationship between the speed at which a vehicle (like an airplane or a boat) is moving forward and the speed at which its propeller is turning.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] It helps in understanding the efficiency of the propeller at different speeds and is particularly useful in the design and analysis of propeller-driven vehicles.It is the ratio of the freestream fluid speed to the propeller, rotor, or cyclorotor tip speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] When a propeller-driven vehicle is moving at high speed relative to the fluid, or the propeller is rotating slowly, the advance ratio of its propeller(s) is a high number.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] When the vehicle is moving at low speed or the propeller is rotating at high speed, the advance ratio is a low number.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] The advance ratio is a useful non-dimensional quantity in helicopter and propeller theory, since propellers and rotors will experience the same angle of attack on every blade airfoil section at the same advance ratio regardless of actual forward speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] It is the inverse of the tip speed ratio used for wind turbines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Low Advance Ratio (J < 1): When the advance ratio is low, the vehicle is moving forward slowly relative to the propeller speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] This usually happens at low speeds or when the propeller is turning very fast.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] High Advance Ratio (J > 1): When the advance ratio is high, the vehicle is moving forward quickly compared to the propeller's rotational speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] This typically occurs at higher speeds or when the propeller is turning more slowly.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] The advance ratio is critical for determining the efficiency of a propeller.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] At different advance ratios, the propeller may produce more or less thrust.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Engineers use this ratio to optimize the design of the propeller and the engine, ensuring that the vehicle operates efficiently at its intended cruising speed, see propeller theory.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] For instance, an airplane's propeller needs to be efficient both during takeoff (where the advance ratio is low) and at cruising altitude (where the advance ratio is higher).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Similarly, a boat's propeller design will vary depending on whether it's designed for slow-speed maneuvering or high-speed travel.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Single rotor helicopters are limited in forward speed by a combination of sonic tip speed and retreating blade stall.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] As the advance ratio increases, the relative velocity experienced by the retreating blade decreases so that the tip of the blade experiences zero velocity at an advance ratio of one.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Helicopter rotors pitch the retreating blade to a higher angle of attack to maintain lift as the relative velocity decreases.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] At a sufficiently high advance ratio, the blade will reach the stalling angle of attack and experience retreating blade stall.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Specially designed airfoils can increase the operating advance ratio by utilizing high lift coefficient airfoils.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Currently, single rotor helicopters are practically limited to advance ratios less than 0.7.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] In operation, propellers and rotors are generally spinning, but could be immersed in a stationary fluid.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Thus the tip speed is placed in the denominator so the advance ratio increases from zero to a positive non-infinite value as the velocity increases.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/advance-ratio] Wind turbines use the reciprocal to prevent infinite values since they start stationary in a moving fluid.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/aeronautics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The **ATR 72** is a twin-engine turboprop, short-haul regional airliner developed and produced in France and Italy by aircraft manufacturer ATR.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The number "72" in its name is derived from the aircraft's typical standard seating capacity of 72 passengers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72 has also been used as a corporate transport, cargo aircraft, and maritime patrol aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] To date, all of the ATR series have been completed at the company's final assembly line in Toulouse, France; ATR benefits from sharing resources and technology with Airbus SE, which has continued to hold a 50% interest in the company.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Successive models of the ATR 72 have been developed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Typical updates have included new avionics, such as a glass cockpit, and the adoption of newer engine versions to deliver enhanced performance, such as increased efficiency and reliability and reductions in operating costs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The aircraft shares a high degree of commonality with the smaller ATR 42, which remains in production as of 2025.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ATR (French: *Avions de transport régional* or Italian: *Aerei da Trasporto Regionale*) is a joint venture formed by French aerospace company Aérospatiale (now part of Airbus) and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia (now Leonardo S.p.A.).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the 1980s, French aerospace company Aérospatiale and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia merged their work on a new generation of regional aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The new jointly owned company, ATR, was established to develop, manufacture, and market their first airliner, later designated the ATR 42.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 16 August 1984, the first model of the series, designated as the ATR 42-300, performed the type's maiden flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, the ATR 72 was developed as a stretched variant of the ATR 42.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 27 October 1989, Finnish airline Finnair became the first airline to operate this type in revenue service.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, ATR sought to introduce a larger airliner with increased capacity over its earlier products.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] This new regional airliner, designated as the ATR 72, was directly developed from the earlier ATR 42 and had much in common with it; the principal difference between the two airliners was an increase in the maximum seating capacity from 48 to 78 passengers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] This was principally achieved by stretching the fuselage by 4.5 m (15 ft), along with an increase of the wingspan, the use of more powerful engines, and increased fuel capacity by about 10%.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 15 January 1986, the launch of the stretched ATR 72 programme was announced.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 27 October 1988, the prototype performed its maiden flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] One year later, on 25 September 1989, the ATR 72 received airworthiness certification from the French Directorate General for Civil Aviation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The following month, on 27 October 1989, Finnish airline Finnair became the first to introduce the aircraft into service.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Since the ATR 72 is assembled on the same production line as the smaller ATR 42, along with sharing the majority of subsystems, components, and manufacturing techniques, the two types support each other to remain in production.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] This factor may have been crucial as, by 2015, the ATR 42 was the only 50-seat regional aircraft still being manufactured.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In 2000, the combined global ATR fleet reached its 10,000,000th flight, during which a distance of around 4 billion km (2.5 billion statute miles) and around 450 million passengers had flown on board ATR-built aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The 2007 production set a new record for the programme's sales; a total of 113 new ATR aircraft had been ordered during a single year.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] By the end of 2014, ATR had received 1,000 orders for the type and delivered 754, leaving a backlog of 246 aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Various organisational changes were implemented within the ATR company.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 10 July 1998, ATR launched its new Asset Management Department.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In June 2001, EADS and Alenia Aeronautica, ATR's parent companies, decided to reinforce their partnership, regrouping all industrial activities related to regional airliners into the ATR consortium.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 3 October 2003, ATR became one of the first aircraft manufacturers to be certified under ISO 9000-2000 and EN/AS/JISQ 9100, the worldwide quality standard for the aeronautics industry.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During July 2004, ATR and Brazilian aircraft manufacturer Embraer announced a co-operation agreement on the AEROChain Portal to deliver improved customer service.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During April 2009, ATR announced the launch of its 'Door-2-Door' service as a new option in its comprehensive customer services range.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] As of October 2007, the current production version is the *ATR 72-600* series.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 2 October 2007, ATR CEO Stéphane Mayer announced the launch of the -600 series aircraft; the ATR 42-600 and ATR 72-600 featured various improvements to increase efficiency, dispatch reliability, lower fuel burn, and operating costs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] While broadly similar to the earlier -500 model, differences include adopting improved PW127M engines, a new glass cockpit, and various other minor improvements.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Since 2008, ATR has been a participant in the European Clean Sky Joint Technology Initiative.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ATR's senior vice-president for engineering Alessandro Amendola indicated that the elimination of all uses of bleed air was a key aim in the designing of an all-electric architecture as well as improving engine efficiency; the minimising of peak electrical loads was also a stated priority.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During March 2016, a second round of flight trials dedicated the testing of all-electric systems architecture using the demonstrator was completed; analysis is set to continue.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Speaking in October 2015, ATR CEO Patrick de Castelbajac stated that the firm was set to produce in excess of 90 aircraft that year, and that the new manufacturing facilities could support a production rate of up to 120 per year.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] At the time, the company had a backlog of orders for 300 aircraft, sufficient for three years of production.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During 2017, a new in-house financing and leasing division was established by ATR in order to offer customers a greater degree of support and expand the company's range of services.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In December 2015, the EASA approved a new high-density seating layout, raising the maximum capacity from 74 to 78 seats.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the 2021 Dubai Airshow in mid-November 2021, ATR debuted the new ATR 72-600 powered by new PW127XT powerplants with 20% lower maintenance cost and 3% lower fuel consumption than the predecessor PW127M powerplant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Considerable emphasis has been placed upon the continuous development of ATR's aircraft models.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Speaking at the Farnborough Airshow in July 2016, the CEO of ATR Patrick de Castelbajac stated that the company was currently examining the possibility of replacing the current Pratt & Whitney Canada PW127 engine with either a new offer from P&WC, or a GE38 derivative from GE Aviation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Although expressing satisfaction with the PW127 engine and its supplier, Castelbajac noted the design's age and the need to remain competitive with the latest regional jets.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] To be a worthwhile exercise, any re-engine exercise would require a 15 per cent improvement in fuel-burn and 20-25 per cent reduction of direct maintenance costs.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Additionally, Castelbajac sees the potential re-engine as a "bridge" to the eventual development of a larger 100-seat aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] However, in January 2018, ATR's parent company Leonardo announced that the 100-seat program has been formally brought to a close.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72 is a turboprop-powered regional airliner, capable of accommodating a maximum of 78 passengers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It is powered by a pair of Pratt & Whitney Canada PW100 turboprop engines, which drive an arrangement of four or six-bladed propellers supplied by Hamilton Standard.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Earlier models of the ATR 72 are equipped with the older PW124B engine, rated at 1,800 kilowatts (2,400 shp), while later-built aircraft are powered by the newer PW127 engine, rated at a maximum of 2,050 kW (2,750 shp) to achieve improved "hot and high" takeoff performance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It can land and takeoff in high airports with short runways like Andorra Airport.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It employs carbonfibres for 30% of the wing by weight, for a 20% weight reduction.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In a standard configuration, the aircraft does not have an auxiliary power unit; when present it is installed within the C4 cargo section.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Most operators of the ATR 72 equip their aircraft with a propeller brake that stops the propeller on the No.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] 2 (right) engine while allowing the turbine to continue running, to provide both airflow and electrical power to the aircraft while on the ground.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] While passengers are boarding or disembarking, a tail stand is set into place as standard procedure to guard against the aircraft nose lifting off the ground.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] 2011 was a record-breaking year for sales at ATR.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] According to ATR's CEO Filippo Bagnato, sales had continued to grow during the Great Recession despite the downturn experienced by most aviation companies as "fuel consumption that can be half that of the alternatives and [with] lower maintenance costs".
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] For 2013, ATR claimed a 48 percent global market share for regional aircraft deliveries between 50 and 90 seats (comprising both turboprops and jets), making it the dominant manufacturer in this market segment.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] That same year, during which firm orders for 10 ATR 42-600s and 79 ATR 72-600s were recorded, leasing companies were responsible for 70 per cent of these; according to ATR's CEO Filippo Bagnato: "Years ago, we were not even considered by the lessors; now they see ATRs as a good investment".
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Placing their first order during 2011, by December 2012, Singaporean lessor Avation had a combined total of 20 ATR 72s on order; by February 2016, the number on order for Avation had risen to 35 aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During May 1997, ATR achieved their first breakthrough sale in China, placed by operator China Xinjiang Airlines and the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During late 2014, ATR set up a new office in Beijing and hired several former Airbus sales personnel with the aim of launching the type in the Chinese market.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ATR believed that many of the already-flown routes did not suit larger 150-seat aircraft; however, of the roughly 2,600 commercial aircraft flying in China at that time, only 68 had a capacity of less than 90 seats and of these, fewer than 20 were powered by turboprop engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During February 2016, ATR signed a deal with flag carrier Iran Air for a batch of 20 ATR 72-600s, along with options for 20 more aircraft and post-purchase services, such as engine maintenance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Made possible by a negotiated relaxation of international sanctions against Iran, during June 2017, a €1 billion Iranian contract was finalized for the firm 20 airliners and 20 options; the delivery of the first four aircraft occurred within weeks of the deal being completed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] US sanctions against Iran were reimposed in August 2018, by which time 13 of the order of 20 aircraft had been delivered.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In April 2019 the US Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) issued a two-year licence to ATR to allow it to supply spare parts and other essentials to keep the fleet of 13 ATR 72-600s in operation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] However, the remaining 7 ATR 72-600s from the 2016 order remain sanctioned and in storage.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] While primarily used as a civil aircraft, some ATR 72s have been adapted to perform in various military functions, such as utility aircraft and maritime patrol aircraft (MPA).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The Turkish Navy, which initially decided to purchase ten ATR 72-500 MPA, later changed its order to eight aircraft: Two ATR 72-600 TMUA (Turkish Maritime Utility Aircraft) versions, and six ATR 72-600 TMPA (Turkish Maritime Patrol Aircraft for MP/ASW/ASuW duties) versions.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The armed ATR 72 TMPA variant was developed in cooperation with Turkish Aerospace Industries (TAI), and incorporated additional sensors and mission systems to perform its intended combat role.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During 2013, the two ATR 72-600 TMUA aircraft were delivered to the Turkish Navy.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The first ATR 72-600 TMPA was delivered in December 2020 and the second one in March 2021 was already in service with Turkish Navy.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] As of May 2021, 3 ATR 72-600 TMUA aircraft are being operated by the Turkish Navy.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The Italian Air Force selected the ATR 72-600 MP, designated as the *P-72A*, to serve as a multirole maritime patrol, electronic surveillance and C4 platform.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The original Italian requirement for a Breguet Atlantic replacement had also called for ASW and anti-surface warfare (ASuW) capabilities, however, during 2014, the contract was renegotiated to a configuration that excluded these capabilities.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] An anticipated variant for ASW and ASuW operations may later be pursued; accordingly, provisions were made to allow for the four P-72As on order to be adapted to the ASW configuration.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In December 2016, the first pair of P-72A aircraft were delivered to the Italian Air Force.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The last aircraft was delivered to the Italian Air Force in February 2021.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] A single ATR 72 MP was ordered by Italy's paramilitary Guardia di Finanza (GdF) in July 2019, followed by an order for a further three ATR 72s in October 2019.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The aircraft, called P-72B by Guardia di Finanza, will supplement the GdF's existing force of four ATR-42s in the border surveillance, maritime patrol and search and rescue roles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] On 8 November 2017, FedEx Express launched the -600 cargo variant with 30 firm orders plus 20 options, in a freighter configuration from the factory.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] As of September 2018, 187 early variants had been produced with 172 operated by 55 carriers, 365 -500s were delivered with more than 350 in service at 75 operators, 444 -600s were produced and are operated by 74 carriers with a backlog of 231 orders.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] By then, with more than 60 -500s and 40 -600s in storage, new aircraft leases fell to $130,000 per month from $170,000.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72 was a candidate to replace the German Navy's P-3, at least as a stopgap solution from 2025 to 2032.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Germany ultimately selected the P-8A Poseidon in 2021.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Two subtypes were marketed as the 100 series (-100).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Initial production variant with front and rear passenger doors, powered by two PW124B engines and certified in September 1989.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Initial production variant with a front cargo door and a rear passenger door, powered by two PW124B engines and certified in December 1989.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Two sub-types were marketed as the 200 series (-200).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The -200 was the original production version, powered by Pratt & Whitney Canada PW124B engines rated at 2,400 shp (1,800 kW).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Higher maximum take-off weight variant of the -101, a PW124B-powered variant certified in September 1989.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Higher maximum take-off weight variant of the -102, a PW124B-powered variant certified in December 1989.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Two subtypes were marketed as the 210 series (-210): the -211 (and with an enlarged cargo door, called the -212) is a -200 with PW127 engines producing 2,750 shp (2,050 kW) each for improved performance in hot and high-altitude conditions.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The subtypes differ in the type of doors and emergency exits.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] PW127-powered variant certified in December 1992.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Certified in January 1997 and fitted with either PW127F or PW127M engines, the -212A is an upgraded version of the -210 using six-bladed propellers on otherwise identical PW127F engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Other improvements include higher maximum weights and superior performance, as well as greater automation of power management to ease pilot workload.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Initial marketing name for the ATR 72-212A.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Marketing name for ATR 72-212A with different equipment fit.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The -600 series aircraft was announced in October 2007; the first deliveries were planned for the second half of 2010.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The prototype ATR 72-600 first flew on 24 July 2009; it had been converted from an ATR 72-500.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72-600 features several improvements.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] engines, which enable a 5% increase in takeoff power via a "boost function" used only when called for by takeoff conditions.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It also features lighter seats and larger overhead baggage bins.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the 2021 Dubai Airshow in mid-November 2021, ATR debuted the new ATR 72-600 engine which is powered by new PW127XT powerplants with 20% lower maintenance cost and 3% lower fuel consumption than the predecessor PW127M powerplant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72-600 HighLine is the same as the ATR 72-600 however it featured an executive cabin layout.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72MP is an ATR 72-600 derivative developed by Leonardo for search and rescue, maritime patrol, command and control, communication, computers, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (C4ISR).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Leonardo Electronics designed its *Airborne Tactical Observation and Surveillance* (ATOS) backbone to manage its sensors, combine their output in a tactical situation presented on up to four workstations.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] A tactical display is added to the glass cockpit and can be integrated with INS/GPS positioning systems and IFF transponder.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Three U/VHF radios, one HF radio and a wideband SATCOM are used for communications.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Other sensors, systems and communications equipment can be integrated, like an electronic support measure (ESM) system.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] A defensive aids sub-system (DASS) is optionally available for operation in hostile areas.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Its capabilities are airborne ocean surface surveillance, telemetry recording and relay.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] , the aircraft can detect a person in a life raft up to 128 km away in the water.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It downlinks this telemetry data to a ground-based surveillance center which is to be integrated to the National Coast Watch Center system.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It has the capability to relay four airborne UHF frequencies over the horizon to ground sites.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Additional Mission Management System (MMS), L-3 Wescam MX-20HD electro-optical sensor system for intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) and Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) capabilities.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] of the -600, 8 November 2017 launch with 30 firm orders from FedEx plus 20 options.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] it was EASA certified by early December.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] FedEx should receive six aircraft per year until 2025, later freighters will fly in the US and in Latin America.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ATR forecasts a market for 460 converted or new-build turboprop freighters over 20 years.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] Bulk Freighter (tube versions) and ULD Freighter (Large Cargo Door).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] , coupled with a dedicated cargo conversion.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] A VIP version of the -500 is available with a luxury interior for executive or corporate transport.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, the company investigated a 78-seat derivative of the ATR 72.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ATR also studied a turbofan version of the proposed ATR 82 (stretched version of the ATR 72) in the early 1990s.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] This proposed version targeted the increasing demand of worldwide cargo and express mail markets, where the aim is to allow operators to supplement their passengers flights with freighter flights.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] In Quick Change configuration, the smoke detector is equipped alongside other modifications required in order to meet the certification for full freight operations.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] ft), facilitating containerised freight loading.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] It takes 30 minutes to convert the ATR 42, and 45 minutes to convert the ATR 72.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The ATR 72 has been involved in 66 aviation accidents and incidents, including 40 hull losses, resulting in 532 fatalities.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] As of August 2024, there have been 13 accidents with at least one fatality reported.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/atr-72] The first fatal accident involving the aircraft was American Eagle Flight 4184 on 31 October 1994, with 68 fatalities, while the most recent accident occurred on 9 August 2024 when Voepass Linhas Aéreas Flight 2283 crashed resulting in 62 fatalities.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In aeronautics, an **aircraft propeller**, also called an **airscrew**, converts rotary motion from an engine or other power source into a swirling slipstream which pushes the propeller forwards or backwards.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] It comprises a rotating power-driven hub, to which are attached several radial airfoil-section blades such that the whole assembly rotates about a longitudinal axis.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The blade pitch may be fixed, manually variable to a few set positions, or of the automatically variable "constant-speed" type.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The propeller attaches to the power source's driveshaft either directly or through reduction gearing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Propellers can be made from wood, metal or composite materials.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Propellers are only useful at subsonic airspeeds generally below about 480 mph (770 km/h), although a speed of Mach 1.01 in a dive was achieved, with a propeller efficiency of 78%, by the McDonnell XF-88B experimental propeller-equipped aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The earliest references for vertical flight came from China.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Since around 400 BC, Chinese children have played with bamboo flying toys.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This bamboo-copter is spun by rolling a stick attached to a rotor between one's hands.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The spinning creates lift, and the toy flies when released.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The 4th-century AD Daoist book *Baopuzi* by Ge Hong (抱朴子 "Master who Embraces Simplicity") reportedly describes some of the ideas inherent to rotary wing aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Designs similar to the Chinese helicopter toy appeared in Renaissance paintings and other works.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] It was not until the early 1480s, when Leonardo da Vinci created a design for a machine that could be described as an "aerial screw", that any recorded advancement was made towards vertical flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] His notes suggested that he built small flying models, but there were no indications for any provision to stop the rotor from making the craft rotate.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] As scientific knowledge increased and became more accepted, man continued to pursue the idea of vertical flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Many of these later models and machines would more closely resemble the ancient bamboo flying top with spinning wings, rather than Leonardo's screw.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In July 1754, Russian Mikhail Lomonosov had developed a small coaxial modeled after the Chinese top but powered by a wound-up spring device and demonstrated it to the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] It was powered by a spring, and was suggested as a method to lift meteorological instruments.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In 1783, Christian de Launoy, and his mechanic, Bienvenu, used a coaxial version of the Chinese top in a model consisting of contrarotating turkey flight feathers as rotor blades, and in 1784, demonstrated it to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A dirigible airship was described by Jean Baptiste Marie Meusnier presented in 1783.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The drawings depict a 260-foot-long (79 m) streamlined envelope with internal ballonets that could be used for regulating lift.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The airship was designed to be driven by three propellers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In 1784 Jean-Pierre Blanchard fitted a hand-powered propeller to a balloon, the first recorded means of propulsion carried aloft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Sir George Cayley, influenced by a childhood fascination with the Chinese flying top, developed a model of feathers, similar to that of Launoy and Bienvenu, but powered by rubber bands.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] By the end of the century, he had progressed to using sheets of tin for rotor blades and springs for power.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] His writings on his experiments and models would become influential on future aviation pioneers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] William Bland sent designs for his "Atmotic Airship" to the Great Exhibition held in London in 1851, where a model was displayed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This was an elongated balloon with a steam engine driving twin propellers suspended underneath.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Alphonse Pénaud developed coaxial rotor model helicopter toys in 1870, also powered by rubber bands.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In 1872 Dupuy de Lome launched a large navigable balloon, which was driven by a large propeller turned by eight men.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Hiram Maxim built a craft that weighed 3.5 long tons (3.6 t), with a 110 ft (34 m) wingspan that was powered by two 360 hp (270 kW) steam engines driving two propellers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In 1894, his machine was tested with overhead rails to prevent it from rising.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The test showed that it had enough lift to take off.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] One of Pénaud's toys, given as a gift by their father, inspired the Wright brothers to pursue the dream of flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The twisted airfoil (aerofoil) shape of an aircraft propeller was pioneered by the Wright brothers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] While some earlier engineers had attempted to model air propellers on marine propellers, the Wrights realized that a propeller is essentially the same as a wing, and were able to use data from their earlier wind tunnel experiments on wings, introducing a twist along the length of the blades.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This was necessary to maintain a more uniform angle of attack of the blade along its length.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Their original propeller blades had an efficiency of about 82%, compared to 90% for a modern (2010) small general aviation propeller, the 3-blade McCauley used on a Beechcraft Bonanza aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Roper quotes 90% for a propeller for a human-powered aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Mahogany was the wood preferred for propellers through World War I, but wartime shortages encouraged use of walnut, oak, cherry and ash.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Alberto Santos Dumont was another early pioneer, having designed propellers before the Wright Brothers for his airships.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] He applied the knowledge he gained from experiences with airships to make a propeller with a steel shaft and aluminium blades for his 14 bis biplane in 1906.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Some of his designs used a bent aluminium sheet for blades, thus creating an airfoil shape.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] They were heavily undercambered, and this plus the absence of lengthwise twist made them less efficient than the Wright propellers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Even so, this was perhaps the first use of aluminium in the construction of an airscrew.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Originally, a rotating airfoil behind the aircraft, which pushes it, was called a propeller, while one which pulled from the front was a tractor.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Later the term 'pusher' became adopted for the rear-mounted device in contrast to the tractor configuration and both became referred to as 'propellers' or 'airscrews'.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The understanding of low speed propeller aerodynamics was fairly complete by the 1920s, but later requirements to handle more power in a smaller diameter have made the problem more complex.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Propeller research for National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA) was directed by William F.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Parameters measured included propeller efficiency, thrust developed, and power absorbed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] While a propeller may be tested in a wind tunnel, its performance in free-flight might differ.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] At the Langley Memorial Aeronautical Laboratory, E.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Leslie used Vought VE-7s with Wright E-4 engines for data on free-flight, while Durand used reduced size, with similar shape, for wind tunnel data.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Their results were published in 1926 as NACA report #220.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Lowry quotes a propeller efficiency of about 73.5% at cruise for a Cessna 172.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This is derived from his "Bootstrap approach" for analyzing the performance of light general aviation aircraft using fixed pitch or constant speed propellers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The efficiency of the propeller is influenced by the angle of attack (α).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This is defined as α = Φ - θ, where θ is the helix angle (the angle between the resultant relative velocity and the blade rotation direction) and Φ is the blade pitch angle.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Very small pitch and helix angles give a good performance against resistance but provide little thrust, while larger angles have the opposite effect.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The best helix angle is when the blade is acting as a wing producing much more lift than drag.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] However, 'lift-and-drag' is only one way to express the aerodynamic force on the blades.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] To explain aircraft and engine performance the same force is expressed slightly differently in terms of thrust and torque since the required output of the propeller is thrust.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Thrust and torque are the basis of the definition for the efficiency of the propeller as shown below.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The advance ratio of a propeller is similar to the angle of attack of a wing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Propellers are similar in aerofoil section to a low-drag wing and as such are poor in operation when at other than their optimum angle of attack.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Therefore, most propellers use a variable pitch mechanism to alter the blades' pitch angle as engine speed and aircraft velocity are changed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A further consideration is the number and the shape of the blades used.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Increasing the aspect ratio of the blades reduces drag but the amount of thrust produced depends on blade area, so using high-aspect blades can result in an excessive propeller diameter.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A further balance is that using a smaller number of blades reduces interference effects between the blades, but to have sufficient blade area to transmit the available power within a set diameter means a compromise is needed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Increasing the number of blades also decreases the amount of work each blade is required to perform, limiting the local Mach number – a significant performance limit on propellers.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The performance of a propeller suffers when transonic flow first appears on the tips of the blades.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] As the relative air speed at any section of a propeller is a vector sum of the aircraft speed and the tangential speed due to rotation, the flow over the blade tip will reach transonic speed well before the aircraft does.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] When the airflow over the tip of the blade reaches its critical speed, drag and torque resistance increase rapidly and shock waves form creating a sharp increase in noise.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Aircraft with conventional propellers, therefore, do not usually fly faster than Mach 0.6.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] There have been propeller aircraft which attained up to the Mach 0.8 range, but the low propeller efficiency at this speed makes such applications rare.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The tip of a propeller blade travels faster than the hub.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Therefore, it is necessary for the blade to be twisted so as to decrease the angle of attack of the blade gradually and therefore produce uniform lift from the hub to the tip.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The greatest angle of incidence, or the highest pitch, is at the hub while the smallest angle of incidence or smallest pitch is at the tip.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A propeller blade designed with the same angle of incidence throughout its entire length would be inefficient because as airspeed increases in flight, the portion near the hub would have a negative AOA while the blade tip would be stalled.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] There have been efforts to develop propellers and propfans for aircraft at high subsonic speeds.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The 'fix' is similar to that of transonic wing design.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Thin blade sections are used and the blades are swept back in a scimitar shape (scimitar propeller) in a manner similar to wing sweepback, so as to delay the onset of shockwaves as the blade tips approach the speed of sound.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The maximum relative velocity is kept as low as possible by careful control of pitch to allow the blades to have large helix angles.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] More blades are used to reduce the work per blade and so circulation strength.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The propellers designed are more efficient than turbo-fans and their cruising speed (Mach 0.7–0.85) is suitable for airliners, but the noise generated is extremely high (see the Antonov An-70 and Tupolev Tu-95 for examples of such a design).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Forces acting on the blades of an aircraft propeller include the following.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Some of these forces can be arranged to counteract each other, reducing the overall mechanical stresses imposed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Thrust loads on the blades, in reaction to the force pushing the air backwards, act to bend the blades forward.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] forwards, such that the outward centrifugal force of rotation acts to bend them backwards, thus balancing out the bending effects.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A centrifugal twisting force is experienced by any asymmetrical spinning object.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In the propeller it acts to twist the blades to a fine pitch.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] is therefore usually arranged to be slightly forward of its mechanical centreline, creating a twisting moment towards coarse pitch and counteracting the centrifugal moment.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] However in a high-speed dive the aerodynamic force can change significantly and the moments can become unbalanced.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The force felt by the blades acting to pull them away from the hub when turning.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] It can be arranged to help counteract the thrust bending force, as described above.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] effects causes propeller blades to bend away from the direction of rotation.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Many types of disturbance set up vibratory forces in blades.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] These include aerodynamic excitation as the blades pass close to the wing and fuselage.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Piston engines introduce torque impulses which may excite vibratory modes of the blades and cause fatigue failures.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Torque impulses are not present when driven by a gas turbine engine.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The purpose of varying pitch angle is to maintain an optimal angle of attack for the propeller blades, giving maximum efficiency throughout the flight regime.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Only by maximising propeller efficiency at high speeds can the highest possible speed be achieved.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Effective angle of attack decreases as airspeed increases, so a coarser pitch is required at high airspeeds.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The requirement for pitch variation is shown by the propeller performance during the Schneider Trophy competition in 1931.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The Fairey Aviation Company fixed-pitch propeller used was partially stalled on take-off and up to 160 mph (260 km/h) on its way up to a top speed of 407.5 mph (655.8 km/h).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The very wide speed range was achieved because some of the usual requirements for aircraft performance did not apply.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] There was no compromise on top-speed efficiency, the take-off distance was not restricted to available runway length and there was no climb requirement.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The variable pitch blades used on the Tupolev Tu-95 propel it at a speed exceeding the maximum once considered possible for a propeller-driven aircraft using an exceptionally coarse pitch.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Early pitch control settings were pilot operated, either with a small number of preset positions or continuously variable.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The simplest mechanism is the ground-adjustable propeller, which may be adjusted on the ground, but is effectively a fixed-pitch prop once airborne.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The spring-loaded "two-speed" VP prop is set to fine for takeoff, and then triggered to coarse once in cruise, the propeller remaining coarse for the remainder of the flight.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] After World War I, automatic propellers were developed to maintain an optimum angle of attack.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This was done by balancing the centripetal twisting moment on the blades and a set of counterweights against a spring and the aerodynamic forces on the blade.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Automatic props had the advantage of being simple, lightweight, and requiring no external control, but a particular propeller's performance was difficult to match with that of the aircraft's power plant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The most common variable pitch propeller is the constant-speed propeller.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This is controlled by a hydraulic constant speed unit (CSU).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] It automatically adjusts the blade pitch in order to maintain a constant engine speed for any given power control setting.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Constant-speed propellers allow the pilot to set a rotational speed according to the need for maximum engine power or maximum efficiency, and a propeller governor acts as a closed-loop controller to vary propeller pitch angle as required to maintain the selected engine speed.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In most aircraft this system is hydraulic, with engine oil serving as the hydraulic fluid.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] However, electrically controlled propellers were developed during World War II and saw extensive use on military aircraft, and have recently seen a revival in use on home-built aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Another design is the V-Prop, which is self-powering and self-governing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] On most variable-pitch propellers, the blades can be rotated parallel to the airflow to stop rotation of the propeller and reduce drag when the engine fails or is deliberately shut down.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This is called *feathering*, a term borrowed from rowing.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] On single-engined aircraft, whether a powered glider or turbine-powered aircraft, the effect is to increase the gliding distance.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] On a multi-engine aircraft, feathering the propeller on an inoperative engine reduces drag, and helps the aircraft maintain speed and altitude with the operative engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Feathering also prevents *windmilling*, the turning of engine components by the propeller rotation forced by the slipstream; windmilling can damage the engine, start a fire, or cause structural damage to the aircraft.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Most feathering systems for reciprocating engines sense a drop in oil pressure and move the blades toward the feather position, and require the pilot to pull the propeller control back to disengage the high-pitch stop pins before the engine reaches idle RPM.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Turboprop control systems usually use a *negative torque sensor* in the reduction gearbox, which moves the blades toward feather when the engine is no longer providing power to the propeller.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Depending on design, the pilot may have to push a button to override the high-pitch stops and complete the feathering process or the feathering process may be automatic.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Accidental feathering is dangerous and can result in an aerodynamic stall; as seen for example with Yeti Airlines Flight 691 which crashed during approach due to accidental feathering.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The propellers on some aircraft can operate with a negative blade pitch angle, and thus reverse the thrust from the propeller.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Reverse thrust is used to help slow the aircraft after landing and is particularly advantageous when landing on a wet runway as wheel braking suffers reduced effectiveness.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] In some cases reverse pitch allows the aircraft to taxi in reverse – this is particularly useful for getting floatplanes out of confined docks.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Counter-rotating propellers are sometimes used on twin-engine and multi-engine aircraft with wing-mounted engines.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] These propellers turn in opposite directions from their counterpart on the other wing to balance out the torque and p-factor effects.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] They are sometimes referred to as "handed" propellers since there are left hand and right hand versions of each prop.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Generally, the propellers on both engines of most conventional twin-engined aircraft spin clockwise (as viewed from the rear of the aircraft).
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] A contra-rotating propeller or contra-prop places two counter-rotating propellers on concentric drive shafts so that one sits immediately 'downstream' of the other propeller.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] This provides the benefits of counter-rotating propellers for a single powerplant.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] The forward propeller provides the majority of the thrust, while the rear propeller also recovers energy lost in the swirling motion of the air in the propeller slipstream.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] Contra-rotation also increases the ability of a propeller to absorb power from a given engine, without increasing propeller diameter.
[src:propeller-aeronautics/propeller-aeronautics] However the added cost, complexity, weight and noise of the system rarely make it worthwhile and it is only used on high-performance types where ultimate performance is more important than efficiency.
